g.text: Day 11: Git Devops
Commands & Interview Q&A
1: git init:
- This command will initialize a local git repository on your machine.
- When git init is used a .git folder is created which is responsible for
tracking the files and security aspects of the files.
2: git status:
- This will give the status of the files, like which files are currently
being tracked, what changes are made etc.
3: git add:
- This will add the file, into git for tracking, i.e we are telling git
to track this file using git add command.
4: git commit -m " ":
- The changes that were made into the file are ok or are correct
then we save the changes, so to save the changes we use this
command.
5: git push:
- To take the files from your computer to the remote repo
or online folder we use this command.
Q: What is the git workflow you use in your org??
--> git add, git commit, git push
6: git clone:
- to pull or download the code from remote repo to your local
machine we use git clone command.
Q: Difference between Clone and Fork??
----> Fork is used to create a copy of repository
Clone is used to download the repository.
7: git checkout -b "branch name" :
- This will create a new branch from the master/main branch.
8: git branch:
- this command is used to see in which branch you are currently
working.
9: git checkout "branch name":
- This command is used to switch between the branches.
Merging the branches??
- To merge the changes of branches to our main/master branch
we use following 3 commands.
1: git merge
2: git rebase
3: git cherry-pick
- git cherry-pick:
. If we want to just merge any particular commit into our
main branch we use this command.
. this command is not feasible if there are 100s of commits.
git rebase VS git merge :
- git rebase and merge does the same thing but there is
just small diffrence that is if we use git merge the changes are
are updated at the top.
- eg: we have 1 main branch, 1 feature branch, 1 test branch
now suppose a new file is added in all three branches
and we use git merge command to add feature and test branch to main
then it will be merged in following way
changes from feature branch
changes from main branch
and if we use git rebase then it will be merged in following way
changes from main branch
changes from test branch
** In a nutshell git rebase will organize the changes or commits in
more linear way wereas git merge will not. **
